Gauged 𝑳𝝁subscript𝑳𝝁L_{\mu}-𝑳𝝉subscript𝑳𝝉L_{\tau} Model with an Inverse Seesaw Mechanism for Neutrino Masses

Abhish Dev adev@umd.edu
Abstract

In this paper, we propose a GL−R×U​(1)Lμ−Lτsubscript𝐺𝐿𝑅𝑈subscript1subscript𝐿𝜇subscript𝐿𝜏G_{L-R}\times U(1)_{L_{\mu}-L_{\tau}} gauge-symmetric model where GL−Rsubscript𝐺𝐿𝑅G_{L-R} is the left-right gauge symmetry and Lisubscript𝐿𝑖L_{i} is the i−limit-from𝑖i-flavor lepton number. We use the spontaneous breaking (SSB) of U​(1)Lμ−Lτ𝑈subscript1subscript𝐿𝜇subscript𝐿𝜏U(1)_{L_{\mu}-L_{\tau}} to resolve two discrepancies in the standard model: discrepancy in the measured muon anomalous magnetic moment and the small masses of left-handed neutrinos and its oscillations. The massive neutral gauge boson, Zμ​τsubscript𝑍𝜇𝜏Z_{\mu\tau}, arising from the SSB can provide additional contributions to the muon anomalous magnetic moment. In order to explain neutrino masses, we employ the low-energy inverse seesaw mechanism by adding three GL−Rsubscript𝐺𝐿𝑅G_{L-R} singlet fermions, Se,μ,τsubscript𝑆𝑒𝜇𝜏S_{e,\mu,\tau}. The light neutrino mass matrix from the inverse seesaw formula has a specific two-zero texture pattern referred in the literature as the Type-C two-zero texture, due to the U​(1)Lμ−Lτ𝑈subscript1subscript𝐿𝜇subscript𝐿𝜏U(1)_{L_{\mu}-L_{\tau}} symmetry. This allows us to predict the values of the CP-violating Dirac phase, Majorana phases, and the absolute value of light neutrino masses in terms of the precisely measured mixing angles and mass squared differences. The model accommodates a quasi-degenerate spectrum of neutrino masses with inverted ordering. The calculated best-fit value of δC​Psubscript𝛿𝐶𝑃\delta_{CP} surprisingly matches with the current experimentally measured best-fit value of δC​Psubscript𝛿𝐶𝑃\delta_{CP} in Capozzi:2017ipn . At 1​σ1𝜎1\sigma, the measured value of δC​Psubscript𝛿𝐶𝑃\delta_{CP} favors a θ23>π/4subscript𝜃23𝜋4\theta_{23}>\pi/4. At 1​σ1𝜎1\sigma, most of the parameter space is within the cosmological bound on the sum of neutrino mass and the bound on the effective Majorana mass from neutrinoless beta decay.

1 Introduction

The standard model (SM) can explain most of the observed particle phenomena as we know today. However, there is evidence of new physics in unexplained phenomena such as neutrino masses and oscillations, dark matter, and discrepancies in the experimentally measured value of muon anomalous magnetic moment. One of the ways to build on SM is to extend its gauge structure with the simplest extension being that of an Abelian U​(1)X𝑈subscript1𝑋U(1)_{X} symmetry. Standard model, in addition to its gauge symmetry, has some accidental global U​(1)𝑈1U(1) symmetries like the baryon number (B)𝐵(B), flavor lepton numbers (Le,Lμ,subscript𝐿𝑒subscript𝐿𝜇L_{e},\leavevmode\nobreak\ L_{\mu}, and Lτsubscript𝐿𝜏L_{\tau}), and the total lepton number (L=Le+Lμ+Lτ𝐿subscript𝐿𝑒subscript𝐿𝜇subscript𝐿𝜏L=L_{e}+L_{\mu}+L_{\tau}). It is possible to promote some combinations of these symmetries to local gauge symmetries in an anomaly-free manner. These combinations are Le−Lμ,Lμ−Lτsubscript𝐿𝑒subscript𝐿𝜇subscript𝐿𝜇subscript𝐿𝜏L_{e}-L_{\mu},\leavevmode\nobreak\ L_{\mu}-L_{\tau}, and Le−Lτsubscript𝐿𝑒subscript𝐿𝜏L_{e}-L_{\tau} where the anomalies cancel among the different generations of leptonsFoot:1990mn ; He:1990pn ; Foot:1994vd ; Ma:2001md . Out of these three combinations, the most popular one for model building is Lμ−Lτsubscript𝐿𝜇subscript𝐿𝜏L_{\mu}-L_{\tau} which has been used in Xing:2015fdg ; Brignole:2004ah ; Mohapatra:2005yu ; Xing:2006xa ; Adhikary:2006rf ; Kitabayashi:2005fc ; Baek:2008nz ; He:2011kn ; Ge:2010js ; EstebanPretel:2007yq ; Heeck:2011wj ; Joshipura:2009tg ; Fuki:2006ag ; Aizawa:2005yy ; Adhikary:2009kz ; Grimus:2012hu ; Grimus:2005jk ; Rodejohann:2005ru ; Haba:2006hc ; Joshipura:2009fu ; Xing:2010ez ; Bandyopadhyay:2009xa ; Grimus:2006jz ; Fukuyama:1997ky ; Araki:2010kq ; Feng:2012jn ; Kile:2014jea ; Kim:2015fpa ; Zhao:2016orh ; Patra:2016shz . The U​(1)Lμ−Lτ𝑈subscript1subscript𝐿𝜇subscript𝐿𝜏U(1)_{L_{\mu}-L_{\tau}} gauge symmetry has been used to explain leptogenesisChun:2007vh ; Ota:2006xr ; Adhikary:2006rf , dark matterBaek:2017sew ; Biswas:2016yjr ; Altmannshofer:2016jzy ; Biswas:2016yan ; Baek:2015fea ; Das:2013jca , baryon asymmetry, cosmic neutrino spectrum, muon (g-2)Biswas:2016yjr ; Biswas:2016yan ; Patra:2016shz ; Altmannshofer:2016oaq ; Baek:2015fea ; Araki:2014ona ; Harigaya:2013twa ; Ma:2001md , neutrino massesChen:2017gvf ; Asai:2017ryy ; Biswas:2016yjr ; Biswas:2016yan ; Chun:2007vh ; Adhikary:2006rf ; Rodejohann:2005ru ; Ma:2001md , and B anomalies at the LHCb and Belle experimentsBaek:2017sew ; Chen:2017usq ; Altmannshofer:2016jzy ; Crivellin:2015mga .

In this paper, we propose a U​(1)Lμ−Lτ𝑈subscript1subscript𝐿𝜇subscript𝐿𝜏U(1)_{L_{\mu}-L_{\tau}} gauge model which can explain both the muon anomalous magnetic moment and the small neutrino masses. This strategy is suitable because a U​(1)Lμ−Lτ𝑈subscript1subscript𝐿𝜇subscript𝐿𝜏U(1)_{L_{\mu}-L_{\tau}} gauge model automatically satisfies μ−τ𝜇𝜏\mu-\tau permutation symmetry in the leading order thereby naturally accommodating a maximal θ23subscript𝜃23\theta_{23} and a vanishing θ13subscript𝜃13\theta_{13}. The U​(1)Lμ−Lτ𝑈subscript1subscript𝐿𝜇subscript𝐿𝜏U(1)_{L_{\mu}-L_{\tau}} gauge symmetry is not an exact symmetry and must be broken due to the non-vanishing VEV of an Lμ−Lτsubscript𝐿𝜇subscript𝐿𝜏{L_{\mu}-L_{\tau}} charged Higgs field. This spontaneous symmetry breaking (SSB) of the U​(1)Lμ−Lτ𝑈subscript1subscript𝐿𝜇subscript𝐿𝜏U(1)_{L_{\mu}-L_{\tau}} then provides the necessary mass splitting and deviations from maximal θ23subscript𝜃23\theta_{23} and vanishing θ13subscript𝜃13\theta_{13}. Lepton flavor violations in Lμ−Lτsubscript𝐿𝜇subscript𝐿𝜏L_{\mu}-L_{\tau} models is analyzed in Heeck:2014qea . The neutral gauge boson arising from the SSB, Zμ​τsubscript𝑍𝜇𝜏Z_{\mu\tau}, can provide additional contributions to rectify the discrepancy between the theoretically calculated and the experimentally measured values of muon g−2𝑔2g-2. Zμ​τsubscript𝑍𝜇𝜏Z_{\mu\tau} will not couple to the electron or quarks making it insular to the constraints from hadron and lepton colliders. The scope of detecting Zμ​τsubscript𝑍𝜇𝜏Z_{\mu\tau} at the BELLE II Chen:2017cic ; Araki:2017wyg ; Kaneta:2016uyt , NA64 experiment at CERNGninenko:2014pea ; Banerjee:2017hhz , and neutrino beam experiments Kaneta:2016uyt has been widely investigated in previous studies.

A series of CERN experiments and E821 experiment at the Brookhaven National Laboratory(BNL) have reported an anomaly between the experimentally measured value of muon (g-2) and its SM prediction. The strongest constraint in the gμ​τ−mZμ​τsubscript𝑔𝜇𝜏subscript𝑚subscript𝑍𝜇𝜏g_{\mu\tau}-m_{Z_{\mu\tau}} parameter space comes from the neutrino trident cross sectionAltmannshofer:2014pba which is measured in the CHARM IIGeiregat:1990gz and CCFR experimentsMishra:1991bv . Constraints on Zμ​τsubscript𝑍𝜇𝜏Z_{\mu\tau} from LHC are analyzed in Elahi:2017ppe ; Elahi:2015vzh . In section 3, we show that accommodating muon g-2 strongly limits the breaking scale of U​(1)Lμ−Lτ𝑈subscript1subscript𝐿𝜇subscript𝐿𝜏U(1)_{L_{\mu}-L_{\tau}} to be in the range 12-800 GeV.

One of the long-standing issues in physics is the existence of light left-handed neutrinos which the SM predicts to be massless. Neutrino oscillation experiments and cosmological observations have confirmed the existence of three flavors of neutrinos which mix with the values of oscillation parameters given in the table.2 which are the most recently updated values taken from Capozzi:2017ipn . The small neutrino masses can be elegantly realized by using seesaw mechanisms. In the type-I, -II, and -III seesaw models, the total lepton number is spontaneously broken at a high scale, ΛΛ\Lambda, which generates sub-eV masses via the seesaw formula mν=v2Λsubscript𝑚𝜈superscript𝑣2Λm_{\nu}=\frac{v^{2}}{\Lambda}, where v𝑣v is the electroweak scale. However, this also pushes ΛΛ\Lambda beyond the multi-TeV scales making the new physics inaccessible at the LHC. Using the spontaneous symmetry breaking of U​(1)Lμ−Lτ𝑈subscript1subscript𝐿𝜇subscript𝐿𝜏U(1)_{L_{\mu}-L_{\tau}} to explain both muon anomalous magnetic moment and neutrino masses has been realized in various models in the context of Type I seesaw mechanismBiswas:2016yjr ; Biswas:2016yan ; Patra:2016shz . Since U​(1)Lμ−Lτ𝑈subscript1subscript𝐿𝜇subscript𝐿𝜏U(1)_{L_{\mu}-L_{\tau}} has to be broken in the GeV scale, it is natural to prefer a low energy seesaw mechanism like the inverse seesaw mechanism over type-I, -II, and -III seesaw mechanisms.

The inverse seesaw mechanism often referred in the literature as the double seesaw mechanism is a low-energy seesaw mechanism in which low energy gauge singlet fermions, S𝑆S, are added in addition to the right-handed neutrinos, NRsubscript𝑁𝑅N_{R}, to obtain sub-eV left-handed neutrinos, νLsubscript𝜈𝐿\nu_{L}Mohapatra:1986aw ; Mohapatra:1986bd ; GonzalezGarcia:1988rw ; Deppisch:2004fa . In general, the number of sterile fermions can be different from the number of neutrino species. In the basis (νL,NRc,S)subscript𝜈𝐿subscriptsuperscript𝑁𝑐𝑅𝑆(\nu_{L},\leavevmode\nobreak\ N^{c}_{R},\leavevmode\nobreak\ S), the lepton mass matrix takes the following peculiar form.

Mν=(0mD0mD0mN0mNμ).subscript𝑀𝜈0subscript𝑚𝐷0subscript𝑚𝐷0subscript𝑚𝑁0subscript𝑚𝑁𝜇M_{\nu}=\left(\begin{array}[]{ccc}0&m_{D}&0\\ m_{D}&0&m_{N}\\ 0&m_{N}&\mu\\ \end{array}\right). (1)

where the matrices MNsubscript𝑀𝑁M_{N}, mDsubscript𝑚𝐷m_{D}, and μ𝜇\mu are in general complex. In the hierarchy μ≪mD≪Mmuch-less-than𝜇subscript𝑚𝐷much-less-than𝑀\mu\ll m_{D}\ll M, the effective light neutrino mass matrix can be approximated as

mν=mDT​(mNT)−1​μ​mN​mD.subscript𝑚𝜈superscriptsubscript𝑚𝐷𝑇superscriptsuperscriptsubscript𝑚𝑁𝑇1𝜇subscript𝑚𝑁subscript𝑚𝐷m_{\nu}=m_{D}^{T}(m_{N}^{T})^{-1}\mu m_{N}m_{D}. (2)

This is the inverse seesaw formula. As opposed to the Type-I seesaw mechanism, it is possible to have the right-handed neutrinos in the TeV scale thereby providing new physics which is testable at the LHC.

In SM, it is not possible to achieve the peculiar pattern in eq.(1). The zero in (ν,S)𝜈𝑆(\nu,S) positions of Mνsubscript𝑀𝜈M_{\nu} is usually a result of additional symmetries beyond the SM gauge symmetry. An elegant realization of this peculiar form in eq.(1) can be found in the well-studied left-right symmetric (L-R) modelsPati:1974yy ; Mohapatra:1974hk ; Senjanovic:1975rk ; Senjanovic:1978ev ; Mohapatra:1980yp ; Lim:1981kv as pointed out in Dev:2009aw . In this class of models, the SM gauge symmetry is enhanced to S​U​(3)C×S​U​(2)L×S​U​(2)R×U​(1)B−L𝑆𝑈subscript3𝐶𝑆𝑈subscript2𝐿𝑆𝑈subscript2𝑅𝑈subscript1𝐵𝐿SU(3)_{C}\times SU(2)_{L}\times SU(2)_{R}\times U(1)_{B-L} where B𝐵B and L𝐿L are baryon and lepton numbers respectively. An attractive feature of these models is the replacement of the ad-hoc hyper charge, Y𝑌Y, of the SM with the well-motivated B−L𝐵𝐿B-L quantum number. Analogous to the left-handed fermion S​U​(2)L𝑆𝑈subscript2𝐿SU(2)_{L} doublets in the SM, right-handed fermions are S​U​(2)R𝑆𝑈subscript2𝑅SU(2)_{R} doublets in the L-R models. The L-R lagrangian preserves parity symmetry which is spontaneously broken at a scale well above the electroweak scale. L-R models also have a richer Higgs sector to enable these symmetry breaking patterns. The quark and charged lepton masses are obtained by introducing an S​U​(2)L×S​U​(2)R𝑆𝑈subscript2𝐿𝑆𝑈subscript2𝑅SU(2)_{L}\times SU(2)_{R} bi-doublet ϕitalic-ϕ\phi. In the minimal L-R model with gauge triplet Higgs, light neutrino masses are obtained by a combination of Type-I and Type-II seesaw mechanisms.

Putting all these ingredients together, we get an S​U​(3)C×S​U​(2)L×S​U​(2)R×U​(1)B−L×U​(1)Lμ−Lτ𝑆𝑈subscript3𝐶𝑆𝑈subscript2𝐿𝑆𝑈subscript2𝑅𝑈subscript1𝐵𝐿𝑈subscript1subscript𝐿𝜇subscript𝐿𝜏SU(3)_{C}\times SU(2)_{L}\times SU(2)_{R}\times U(1)_{B-L}\times U(1)_{L_{\mu}-L_{\tau}} non-Abelian gauge theory which spontaneously breaks to S​U​(3)C×U​(1)e​m𝑆𝑈subscript3𝐶𝑈subscript1𝑒𝑚SU(3)_{C}\times U(1)_{em}. We employ an L-R singlet but U​(1)Lμ−Lτ𝑈subscript1subscript𝐿𝜇subscript𝐿𝜏U(1)_{L_{\mu}-L_{\tau}} charged Higgs, δ𝛿\delta, to break the U​(1)Lμ−Lτ𝑈subscript1subscript𝐿𝜇subscript𝐿𝜏U(1)_{L_{\mu}-L_{\tau}} completely. An S​U​(2)R𝑆𝑈subscript2𝑅SU(2)_{R} doublet Higgs, χRsubscript𝜒𝑅\chi_{R}, spontaneously breaks GL−Rsubscript𝐺𝐿𝑅G_{L-R} to GS​Msubscript𝐺𝑆𝑀G_{SM} and an S​U​(2)L×S​U​(2)R𝑆𝑈subscript2𝐿𝑆𝑈subscript2𝑅SU(2)_{L}\times SU(2)_{R} bi-doublet Higgs, ϕitalic-ϕ\phi, which carries out the further breaking of GS​Msubscript𝐺𝑆𝑀G_{SM} to S​U​(3)C×U​(1)e​m𝑆𝑈subscript3𝐶𝑈subscript1𝑒𝑚SU(3)_{C}\times U(1)_{em} at the electroweak scale. In the fermionic sector, we add three right-handed neutrinos (Ne,Nμ,Nτ)subscript𝑁𝑒subscript𝑁𝜇subscript𝑁𝜏(N_{e},N_{\mu},N_{\tau}) and three L-R singlet fermions (Se,Sμ,Sτsubscript𝑆𝑒subscript𝑆𝜇subscript𝑆𝜏S_{e},S_{\mu},S_{\tau}) where the subscript denotes their respective flavor lepton number. After SSB, the mass matrix in the basis (νL,NR,S)subscript𝜈𝐿subscript𝑁𝑅𝑆(\nu_{L},N_{R},S) takes the desired form in eq.(1) and the inverse seesaw formula can be used to calculate the approximate light neutrino masses. A parameter scan reveals that this model can only accommodate the inverted ordering of light neutrino masses with a quasi-degenerate hierarchy. In sections 2 and 4, we will discuss the model and the lepton masses arising from this model in detail.

The U​(1)Lμ−Lτ𝑈subscript1subscript𝐿𝜇subscript𝐿𝜏U(1)_{L_{\mu}-L_{\tau}} symmetry restricts the form of Majorana and Dirac mass matrices mDsubscript𝑚𝐷m_{D}, mNsubscript𝑚𝑁m_{N}, and μ𝜇\mu. mDsubscript𝑚𝐷m_{D} and mNsubscript𝑚𝑁m_{N} are restricted to be diagonal matrices whereas the matrix μ𝜇\mu has zeroes in its (μ,μ)𝜇𝜇(\mu,\mu) and (τ,τ)𝜏𝜏(\tau,\tau) entries. The approximate light neutrino mass matrix mνsubscript𝑚𝜈m_{\nu} calculated using the inverse seesaw formula, therefore, also has zeroes in its (μ,μ)𝜇𝜇(\mu,\mu) and (τ,τ)𝜏𝜏(\tau,\tau) positions. This is one of the seven two-zero neutrino mass textures which can accommodate the current neutrino oscillation data, referred in the literature as the type C pattern. These patterns are studied in Berger:2000zj ; Xing:2002ta ; Kageyama:2002zw ; Xing:2002ap . In the context of U​(1)Lμ−Lτ𝑈subscript1subscript𝐿𝜇subscript𝐿𝜏U(1)_{L_{\mu}-L_{\tau}} models, the type-C two-zero pattern is also realized in models where neutrino masses are radiatively generated Baek:2015mna ; Lee:2017ekw . The two zeroes in mνsubscript𝑚𝜈m_{\nu} lead to four real relations that relate the precisely measured values of the mixing angles (θ13,θ12,and​θ23subscript𝜃13subscript𝜃12andsubscript𝜃23\theta_{13},\leavevmode\nobreak\ \theta_{12},\leavevmode\nobreak\ \text{and}\leavevmode\nobreak\ \theta_{23}) and the mass-squared differences (Δ​m212Δsubscriptsuperscript𝑚221\Delta m^{2}_{21} and Δ​m2Δsuperscript𝑚2\Delta m^{2}) to predict the CP-violating Dirac phase (δC​Psubscript𝛿𝐶𝑃\delta_{CP}), the two Majorana phases (α1,2subscript𝛼12\alpha_{1,2}), and the absolute values of the neutrino masses, misubscript𝑚𝑖m_{i}. The effective Majorana mass of neutrinoless double beta decay (<mβ​βsubscript𝑚𝛽𝛽m_{\beta\beta}>) and the sum of neutrino masses (∑misubscript𝑚𝑖\sum m_{i}) can be then calculated and compared with the constraints from neutrinoless beta decay and cosmology respectively. In section 5, it is shown that the major chunk of the parameter space is well within the current experimental bounds. As expected from the parameter scan, this analysis agrees with the quasi-degenerate, inverted ordering for neutrino mass spectrum and a prediction of δC​Psubscript𝛿𝐶𝑃\delta_{CP} close to the present central value. In contrast, the models based on Type-I seesaw mechanismAsai:2017ryy ; Biswas:2016yjr ; Biswas:2016yan satisfy the type-C pattern of two-zero minor textures with vanishing (μ,μ)𝜇𝜇(\mu,\mu) and (τ,τ)𝜏𝜏(\tau,\tau) entries in the inverse of neutrino mass matrix. The predictions of this texture is analyzed in detail in Asai:2017ryy .

2 The GL−R×U​(1)Lμ−Lτsubscript𝐺𝐿𝑅𝑈subscript1subscript𝐿𝜇subscript𝐿𝜏G_{L-R}\times U(1)_{L_{\mu}-L_{\tau}} Model

In this section, we will discuss the GL−R×U​(1)Lμ−Lτsubscript𝐺𝐿𝑅𝑈subscript1subscript𝐿𝜇subscript𝐿𝜏G_{L-R}\times U(1)_{L_{\mu}-L_{\tau}} gauge-symmetric model that we motivated in the introduction.

In addition to the quarks and leptons in the L-R models, the fermionic sector contains three L-R singlet fermions: Se,Sμ,and​Sτsubscript𝑆𝑒subscript𝑆𝜇andsubscript𝑆𝜏S_{e},\leavevmode\nobreak\ S_{\mu},\leavevmode\nobreak\ \text{and}\leavevmode\nobreak\ S_{\tau} where the subscript indicates their flavor lepton number. The Higgs sector has the usual bi-doublet Higgs, ϕitalic-ϕ\phi, which is the L-R analog of the SM Higgs doublet. The minimal L-R model has S​U​(2)L,R𝑆𝑈subscript2𝐿𝑅SU(2)_{L,R} triplet Higgs fields ΔL,RsubscriptΔ𝐿𝑅\Delta_{L,R} with a B−L𝐵𝐿B-L charge of 2 which generate small neutrino masses through a combination of Type-I and Type-II seesaw mechanisms. In our model, we include S​U​(2)R𝑆𝑈subscript2𝑅SU(2)_{R} doublet χRsubscript𝜒𝑅\chi_{R} with a B-L charge of −11-1 instead of the triplets to get the matrix mNsubscript𝑚𝑁m_{N} in eq.(1). The triplets must be avoided to prevent Majorana masses for νLsubscript𝜈𝐿\nu_{L} and NRsubscript𝑁𝑅N_{R} in eq.(1). The gauge group U​(1)Lμ−Lτ𝑈subscript1subscript𝐿𝜇subscript𝐿𝜏U(1)_{L_{\mu}-L_{\tau}} is completely broken by an L-R singlet Higgs δ𝛿\delta. Since δ𝛿\delta is an L-R singlet, the U​(1)Lμ−Lτ𝑈subscript1subscript𝐿𝜇subscript𝐿𝜏U(1)_{L_{\mu}-L_{\tau}} breaking scale is independent of both the electroweak and parity breaking scales. We choose δ𝛿\delta to have an Lμ−Lτsubscript𝐿𝜇subscript𝐿𝜏L_{\mu}-L_{\tau} charge of ±1plus-or-minus1\pm 1 with both being identical choices. A choice of ±2plus-or-minus2\pm 2 would lead to a block-diagonal neutrino mass matrix which cannot generate the desired oscillation patterns. The fermions and scalars in our models and their assignments under various irreps of the gauge group are given in Table.1.

3 Muon anomalous magnetic moment

The intrinsic spin magnetic moment of a fermion is defined as

μ→=g​Q​e2​m​σ→2,→𝜇𝑔𝑄𝑒2𝑚→𝜎2\vec{\mu}=\frac{gQe}{2m}\frac{\vec{\sigma}}{2}, (9)

where g𝑔g is the gyromagnetic ratio which is predicted to be 222 for free fermions by the Dirac equation. Loop corrections to this value can arise from the interactions in a QFT which can give rise to the anomalous magnetic moment defined as

aμ=g−22.subscript𝑎𝜇𝑔22a_{\mu}=\frac{g-2}{2}. (10)

Calculation of lepton anomalous magnetic moments and its close agreement with experiments were one of the first major successes of QED. In the standard model, contribution to muon g-2 comes from various sectors such as QED, electroweak, and hadronic vacuum polarization effects. The non-perturbative strong interaction effects to muon g-2 is indirectly determined using the hadronic crossection in electron-positron annihilation thereby introducing uncertainties in the calculated value. This calculation is done in Jegerlehner:2009ry which reports a value of aμt​h=1.1659179090​(65)×10−3superscriptsubscript𝑎𝜇𝑡ℎ1.165917909065superscript103a_{\mu}^{th}=1.1659179090(65)\times 10^{-3}. The anomalous magnetic moment of muon has been experimentally measured with high precision first in a series of CERN experiments and then by the E821 experiment at Brookhaven National Laboratory (BNL). The present average experimental value stands at aμe​x​p=1.16592080​(63)×10−3superscriptsubscript𝑎𝜇𝑒𝑥𝑝1.1659208063superscript103a_{\mu}^{exp}=1.16592080(63)\times 10^{-3}Bennett:2004pv . This discrepancy,

Δ​aμ=aμe​x​p−aμt​h=(29.0±9.0)×10−10,Δsubscript𝑎𝜇subscriptsuperscript𝑎𝑒𝑥𝑝𝜇subscriptsuperscript𝑎𝑡ℎ𝜇plus-or-minus29.09.0superscript1010\Delta a_{\mu}=a^{exp}_{\mu}-a^{th}_{\mu}=(29.0\pm 9.0)\times 10^{-10}, (11)

is one of the strongest established discrepancy with the standard model at 3.2​σ3.2𝜎3.2\sigma significance. This has been an inspiration for a lot of model building beyond the SM. A lepton flavor violating Z′superscript𝑍′Z^{\prime} was used to account for this discrepancy in Altmannshofer:2016brv . The U​(1)Lμ−Lτ𝑈subscript1subscript𝐿𝜇subscript𝐿𝜏U(1)_{L_{\mu}-L_{\tau}} gauge boson couples to the muon and can give rise to additional contributions in Fig.1(ii). This contribution is calculated in Gninenko:2001hx ; Baek:2001kca to be

Δ​aμ=gμ​τ28​π2​∫01𝑑x​2​x​(1−x)2(1−x)2+r​x,Δsubscript𝑎𝜇subscriptsuperscript𝑔2𝜇𝜏8superscript𝜋2superscriptsubscript01differential-d𝑥2𝑥superscript1𝑥2superscript1𝑥2𝑟𝑥\Delta a_{\mu}=\frac{g^{2}_{\mu\tau}}{8\pi^{2}}\int_{0}^{1}dx\frac{2x(1-x)^{2}}{(1-x)^{2}+rx}, (12)

where the dimensionless parameter r𝑟r is defined as the square of the ratio of Zμ​τsubscript𝑍𝜇𝜏Z_{\mu\tau} mass to the mass of muon ((MZμ​τ/mμ)2superscriptsubscript𝑀subscript𝑍𝜇𝜏subscript𝑚𝜇2(M_{Z_{\mu\tau}}/m_{\mu})^{2}). The discrepancy in the value of muon g-2 is accommodated by a wide range of values of gμ​τsubscript𝑔𝜇𝜏g_{\mu\tau} and mZμ​τsubscript𝑚subscript𝑍𝜇𝜏m_{Z_{\mu\tau}}. When mZμ​τsubscript𝑚subscript𝑍𝜇𝜏m_{Z_{\mu\tau}} falls below 2​mμ2subscript𝑚𝜇2m_{\mu}, Zμ​τsubscript𝑍𝜇𝜏Z_{\mu\tau} primarily decays into neutrinos and this region is mostly eliminated by neutrino interactionsHarnik:2012ni ; Bilmis:2015lja . The values of gμ​τ>10−3subscript𝑔𝜇𝜏superscript103g_{\mu\tau}>10^{-3} is severely constrained primarily by the neutrino trident cross section in Fig.1(i)Altmannshofer:2014pba which has been measured in CHARM-IIGeiregat:1990gz and CCFR Mishra:1991bv experiments.

Together, these constraints limit the region in gμ​τ−mZμ​τsubscript𝑔𝜇𝜏subscript𝑚subscript𝑍𝜇𝜏g_{\mu\tau}-m_{Z_{\mu\tau}} plane that can accommodate the necessary Δ​aμΔsubscript𝑎𝜇\Delta a_{\mu}. In the following section, we will use this range of values for δ𝛿\delta to fit neutrino masses and oscillation parameters.

5 Predictions from texture analysis

The U​(1)Lμ−Lτ𝑈subscript1subscript𝐿𝜇subscript𝐿𝜏U(1)_{L_{\mu}-L_{\tau}} gauge symmetry restricts the form of Dirac and Majorana mass matrices leaving the light neutrino mass matrix of the form in eq.(22). This mass matrix, mνsubscript𝑚𝜈m_{\nu}, in our model has two zeroes in its (μ,μ)𝜇𝜇(\mu,\mu) and (τ,τ)𝜏𝜏(\tau,\tau) entries. A detailed study of possible neutrino mass matrices with such two-zero structures has been done in Berger:2000zj ; Kageyama:2002zw ; Xing:2002ta ; Kageyama:2002zw ; Xing:2002ap where seven such patterns that can accommodate the current values of neutrino oscillation parameters are identified. Similar analysis of zero structures in the context of minimal extended type-I seesaw models are done in Nath:2016mts . The pattern in our model is usually referred in the literature as the type C pattern. This pattern is also realized in many U​(1)Lμ−Lτ𝑈subscript1subscript𝐿𝜇subscript𝐿𝜏U(1)_{L_{\mu}-L_{\tau}} models where neutrino masses are radiatively generated Baek:2015mna ; Lee:2017ekw and in Chen:2017gvf . In Baek:2015mna ; Lee:2017ekw ; Chen:2017gvf , the type-C pattern and its predictions are discussed in some detail. The two zeroes in mνsubscript𝑚𝜈m_{\nu} can give four real relations among the mixing angles, masses, Majorana, and Dirac phases. Using the precisely measured values of the three mixing angles and the two mass-squared differences, it is possible to predict the values of the remaining four parameters: the two Majorana phases (α1,2subscript𝛼12\alpha_{1,2}), CP-violating Dirac phase (δC​Psubscript𝛿𝐶𝑃\delta_{CP}), and the absolute values of neutrino masses. In this section, we will show that this peculiar two-zero structure of the light neutrino mass matrix makes this model very predictive.

The light neutrino mass matrix is complex symmetric and can be diagonalized through a bi-unitary transformation, U†​mν​U∗=diag​{m1,m2,m3}superscript𝑈†subscript𝑚𝜈superscript𝑈diagsubscript𝑚1subscript𝑚2subscript𝑚3U^{\dagger}m_{\nu}U^{*}=\text{diag}\{m_{1},\leavevmode\nobreak\ m_{2},\leavevmode\nobreak\ m_{3}\}. Since the charged lepton mass matrix is diagonal, we can identify the diagonalizing matrix of the light neutrino mass matrix mνsubscript𝑚𝜈m_{\nu}, U𝑈U, to be the PMNS mixing matrix.

The unphysical phases ϕ1,2,3subscriptitalic-ϕ123\phi_{1,2,3} which arise during the diagonalization can also be uniquely determined as a function of mixing angles and mass-squared differences by demanding that (e,e),(e,μ),𝑒𝑒𝑒𝜇(e,e),(e,\mu), and (e,τ)𝑒𝜏(e,\tau) entries of mass matrix mνsubscript𝑚𝜈m_{\nu} are real. Since all the neutrino oscillation parameters including the unphysical phases can be uniquely determined as a function of mass-squared differences and mixing angles, the entries of mνsubscript𝑚𝜈m_{\nu} are tightly constrained by the current experimental data in its 3​σ3𝜎3\sigma range. This can be particularly seen in the case of the free model parameter ϕitalic-ϕ\phi which is confined to the regions near ±πplus-or-minus𝜋\pm\pi despite being allowed its full range during the parameter scan as seen in Fig.3.

The following analysis does not depend on the values of the parameters of the model such as the Yukawa couplings or the breaking scale of U​(1)Lμ−τ𝑈subscript1subscript𝐿𝜇𝜏U(1)_{L_{\mu}-\tau}. The results in this section are applicable to any model with type-C two-zero texture pattern.

The predictions for best-fit value and n​σ𝑛𝜎n\sigma ranges of δC​Psubscript𝛿𝐶𝑃\delta_{CP}, α2,3subscript𝛼23\alpha_{2,3}, m3subscript𝑚3m_{3}, ∑m𝑚\sum m, and ⟨mβ​β⟩delimited-⟨⟩subscript𝑚𝛽𝛽\langle m_{\beta\beta}\rangle using the values of mixing angles and mass-squared differences from the Table.2 are summarized in the Table.3.

Analogous to the type C two-zero texture in our model, the Lμ−Lτsubscript𝐿𝜇subscript𝐿𝜏L_{\mu}-L_{\tau} gauge symmetric models which employ type-I seesaw mechanism satisfy a two-zero minor texture allowing similar predictionsAsai:2017ryy ; Biswas:2016yjr ; Biswas:2016yan . The two-zero minor textures where two zeroes are present in the inverse of the light neutrino mass matrix is studied in Lavoura:2004tu ; Lashin:2007dm ; Verma:2011kz ; Liao:2013saa . The type-C two-zero minor pattern arising in the minimal Lμ−Lτsubscript𝐿𝜇subscript𝐿𝜏L_{\mu}-L_{\tau} gauge symmetric type-I model is studied in great detail in Asai:2017ryy . The relations between the parameters, in this case, can be obtained by merely replacing the mass ratios m2,3/m1subscript𝑚23subscript𝑚1m_{2,3}/m_{1} with their reciprocals in eq.(5). Complementary to our model, the type-I model only accommodates normal ordering with a quasi-degenerate hierarchy. Because of quasi-degenerate hierarchy in both models, the predictions are similar and most of the differences come from the different experimentally measured values of mixing angles and mass-squared differences for normal and inverted orderings. Unlike our model, the best-fit value of δC​Psubscript𝛿𝐶𝑃\delta_{CP} cannot be accommodated even at 2​σ2𝜎2\sigma range. The mass of the lightest neutrino is also larger in the inverse seesaw model allowing a higher sensitivity to the bounds from cosmology and neutrinoless beta decay. Therefore finalizing the neutrino hierarchy, a more precise measurement of δC​Psubscript𝛿𝐶𝑃\delta_{CP}, or stronger bounds from cosmology and neutrinoless beta decay can distinguish between these two models.

6 Conclusion

By combining three popular ideas in model building, viz., the L-R symmetry, inverse seesaw mechanism, and Lμ−Lτsubscript𝐿𝜇subscript𝐿𝜏L_{\mu}-L_{\tau} gauge symmetry, we propose the GL−R×U​(1)μ−τsubscript𝐺𝐿𝑅𝑈subscript1𝜇𝜏G_{L-R}\times U(1)_{\mu-\tau} gauge symmetric model. The spontaneous symmetry breaking of the U​(1)Lμ−Lτ𝑈subscript1subscript𝐿𝜇subscript𝐿𝜏U(1)_{L_{\mu}-L_{\tau}} allows us to resolve the discrepancy in the measurement of muon’s anomalous magnetic moment and the longstanding puzzles of neutrino masses and oscillations. The best-fit point in the parameter space which accommodates the experimentally measured values of neutrino oscillation parameters and muon anomalous magnetic moment (Δ​aμΔsubscript𝑎𝜇\Delta a_{\mu}) is given in Table.LABEL:fit. The choice of inverse seesaw mechanism provides an added advantage of probing new physics from right-handed neutrinos in the multi-TeV scale.

The presence of two zeros in the neutrino mass matrix from the U​(1)Lμ−Lτ𝑈subscript1subscript𝐿𝜇subscript𝐿𝜏U(1)_{L_{\mu}-L_{\tau}} symmetry makes this model very predictive by providing four relations among the precisely measured values of mixing angles and mass-squared differences to make predictions for CP-violating Dirac phase, Majorana phases, and the absolute value of neutrino masses. These predictions along with their uncertainties coming from the error in the measurement of mixing angles are given in Table.3. We see that in this model, only inverted ordering with a quasi-degenerate ordering is allowed. The predictions of complementary values of δC​Psubscript𝛿𝐶𝑃\delta_{CP} in both octants of θ23subscript𝜃23\theta_{23} allow us to have octant sensitivity in our model. The current experimentally measured best-fit value and 1​σ1𝜎1\sigma range of δC​Psubscript𝛿𝐶𝑃\delta_{CP} mostly favor θ23>π/4subscript𝜃23𝜋4\theta_{23}>\pi/4. The prediction for δC​Psubscript𝛿𝐶𝑃\delta_{CP} from the best-fit values of mixing angles and mass-squared differences surprisingly agrees with the current experimentally measured best-fit value. The large values of light neutrino masses also make this model very sensitive to cosmological bound on the sum of neutrino masses and the effective Majorana mass bounds from neutrinoless double beta decay. Most of the parameter space in the 1​σ1𝜎1\sigma range is allowed by these bounds as shown in Figs. 9 and 10.
